<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<subsection xml:id="sec-determinants-and-matrix-inverses">

  <title>General determinants</title>

    <p>
      In this section we consider square <m>n \times n</m> matrices. Our <em>goal</em> is to find a number, called the <em>determinant</em> that we can calculate for any matrix, which tells us whether or not the matrix is invertible.
    </p>

    <p>
      Let's start with the <m>2 \times 2</m> case. Recall that in <xref ref="thm-2-5-determinant-of-two-by-two"/> we defined the determinant of a <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix
      <me>
        A = \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}
      </me>
      to be <m>\det(A) = ad - bc</m>. It has the required properties of the determinant that we will now define for more general matrices.
    </p>

    <activity>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Find the determinant of the following matrices:
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <me> A = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 1 \\ 4 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</me>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
          <p>
            <me>\det(A) = 3(2) - 1(4) = 6 - 4 = 2</me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <me> B = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 2 \\ 6 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix} </me>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
          <p>
            <me>\det(B) = 3(4) - 2(6) = 12 - 12 = 0</me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </activity>

    <p>
      We use the <m>2 \times 2</m> determinant to define the <m>3 \times 3</m> determinant. The idea is recursive: a <m>3 \times 3</m> determinant is built from <m>2 \times 2</m> determinants. Later, an <m>n \times n</m> determinant will be built from <m>(n-1)\times(n-1)</m> determinants.
    </p>

    <definition>
      <title>Minors of a <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be a <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix. The <term><m>(i,j)</m>-th minor</term> of <m>A</m>, denoted
        </p>
        <me>\operatorname{minor}(A)_{ij},</me>
        <p>
          is the determinant of the <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix obtained from <m>A</m> by deleting row <m>i</m> and column <m>j</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <activity>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Suppose
          <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 4 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 2 \amp 1\ \end{bmatrix}</me>.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate <m>\operatorname{minor}(A)_{11}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
          <p>
            <me>
              \operatorname{minor}(A)_{11} = \det \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} = 3(1) - 2(2) = -1
            </me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate <m>\operatorname{minor}(A)_{23}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
          <p>
            <me>
              \operatorname{minor}(A)_{23} = \det \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} = 1(2) - 2(3) = -4
            </me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </activity>

    <definition>
      <title>Cofactors of a <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix</title>

      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be a <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix. The <term><m>(i,j)</m>-cofactor</term> of <m>A</m>, denoted
        </p>
        <me>\operatorname{cof}(A)_{ij},</me>
        <p>is</p>
        <me>
          \operatorname{cof}(A)_{ij}
          =
          (-1)^{i+j}\operatorname{minor}(A)_{ij}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <activity>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Define
          <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 4 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</me>
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute <m>\operatorname{cof}(A)_{11}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
          <p>
            <me>
              \operatorname{cof}(A)_{11} = (-1)^{1 + 1} \operatorname{minor}(A)_{11} = (1)(-1) = -1
            </me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute <m>\operatorname{cof}(A)_{23}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
          <p>
            <me>
              \operatorname{cof}(A)_{23} = (-1)^{2+3} \operatorname{minor}(A)_{23} = (-1)(-4) = 4
            </me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </activity>

    <definition>
      <title>Determinant of a <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A=[a_{ij}]</m> be a <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix. The <term>determinant</term> of <m>A</m>, denoted <m>\det(A)</m>, is defined by expansion along the first row:
        </p>
        <me>
          \det(A)
          =
          a_{11}\operatorname{cof}(A)_{11}
          +
          a_{12}\operatorname{cof}(A)_{12}
          +
          a_{13}\operatorname{cof}(A)_{13}.
        </me>

        <p>
          This process is called <term>cofactor expansion</term>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <fact>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For a <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix, cofactor expansion along any row or any column gives the same determinant.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </fact>

    <activity>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Let
          <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 4 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</me>.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the determinant of <m>A</m> by expanding along row <m>1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
          <p>
            To calculate the determinant of <m>A</m> by expanding along row <m>1</m>, we write
            <me>
              \det(A) = 1\operatorname{cof}(A)_{11} + 2\operatorname{cof}(A)_{12} + 3\operatorname{cof}(A)_{13}
            </me>.
            We begin by calculating the cofactors:
            <me>
              \operatorname{cof}(A)_{11} = (-1)^{1+1}\det\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} = (1)(3\cdot 1 - 2\cdot 2) = -1
            </me>
            <me>
              \operatorname{cof}(A)_{12} = (-1)^{1+2}\det\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} = (-1)(4\cdot 1 - 2\cdot 3) = 2
            </me>
            <me>
              \operatorname{cof}(A)_{13} = (-1)^{1+3}\det\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 3 \\ 3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} = (1)(8 - 9) = -1
            </me>
            Therefore
            <me>\det(A) = 1(-1) + 2(2) + 3(-1) = -1 + 4 - 3 = 0</me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the determinant of <m>A</m> by expanding along column <m>2</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
          <p>
            To calculate the determinant of <m>A</m> by expanding along column <m>2</m>, we write
            <me>
              \det(A) = 2\operatorname{cof}(A)_{12} + 3\operatorname{cof}(A)_{22} + 2\operatorname{cof}(A)_{32}
            </me>
            We calculate the cofactors:
            <me>
              \operatorname{cof}(A)_{12} = (-1)^{1+2}\det\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} = (-1)(4\cdot 1 - 2\cdot 3) = 2
            </me>
            <me>
              \operatorname{cof}(A)_{22} = (-1)^{2+2}\det\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ 3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} = (1)(1\cdot 1 - 3\cdot 3) = -8
            </me>
            <me>
              \operatorname{cof}(A)_{32} = (-1)^{3+2}\det\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ 4 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} = (-1)(2 - 12) = 10
            </me>.
            Therefore
            <me>
              \det(A) = 2(2) + 3(-8) + 2(10) = 4 - 24 + 20 = 0
            </me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </activity>

    <note>
      <statement>
        <p>
          To track the sign <m>(-1)^{i+j}</m> when computing cofactors, it may be helpful to view the matrix as a checkerboard as below:
          <me>
            \begin{bmatrix} + \amp - \amp + \\ - \amp + \amp - \\ + \amp - \amp + \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
          The sign in the <m>i</m>th row and <m>j</m>th position with be the sign of <m>(-1)^{i+j}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </note>

    <note>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Since any row or column gives the same determinant, choose a row or column with many zeros when possible.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </note>

    <activity>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Compute the determinant of the following matrices:
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <me>
              A = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp-5 \amp 1\\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ -2 \amp -4 \amp 7\end{bmatrix}
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
          <p>
            The second row of <m>A</m> has two zeros, and so expanding along this row will likely result in the simplest computation of the determinant. We write
            <md>
              <mrow>
                \det(A) \amp= 0\cdot\text{cof}(A)_{21} + 1\cdot\text{cof}(A)_{22} + 0\cdot\text{cof}(A)_{23}
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                \amp = \text{cof}(A)_{22}
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                \amp = (-1)^{2+2} \det \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 1\\ -2 \amp 7\end{bmatrix}
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                \amp = (1)(3 \cdot 7 - 1 \cdot (-2))
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                \amp = 21 + 2 = 23
              </mrow>
            </md>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>

      <task xml:id="task-3-1-0-column-example">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <me>B = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp \pi \amp 200\\ 0 \amp 0.03 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 19 \amp -3584\end{bmatrix}</me>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
          <p>
            If we expand the determinant of <m>B</m> along its first column, we find that
            <me>
              \det(B) =  0\cdot\operatorname{cof}(B)_{11} + 0\cdot\operatorname{cof}(B)_{21} + 0\cdot\operatorname{cof}(B)_{31} = 0
            </me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </activity>

    <note>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Whenever a row or column of a matrix only has zeros as entries, expanding along that row shows that the determinant of the matrix is always zero, so no cofactor computations are required.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </note>

    <p>
      Now that <m>3 \times 3</m> determinants have been defined, we can define larger determinants recursively. For a <m>4 \times 4</m> matrix, each minor determinant is a <m>3 \times 3</m> determinant. For a <m>5 \times 5</m> matrix, each minor determinant is a <m>4 \times 4</m> determinant, and so on.
    </p>

    <definition>
      <title>Determinant of a general square matrix</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A=[a_{ij}]</m> be an <m>n\times n</m> matrix with <m>n\ge 4</m>. Assume determinants have already been defined for <m>(n-1)\times(n-1)</m> matrices.
        </p>
        <p>
          The <m>(i,j)</m>-th minor of <m>A</m>, denoted
        </p>
        <me>\operatorname{minor}(A)_{ij},</me>
        <p>
          is the determinant of the <m>(n-1)\times(n-1)</m> matrix obtained from <m>A</m> by deleting row <m>i</m> and column <m>j</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The <m>(i,j)</m>-cofactor of <m>A</m> is
        </p>
        <me>
          \operatorname{cof}(A)_{ij}
          =
          (-1)^{i+j}\operatorname{minor}(A)_{ij}.
        </me>
        <p>
          The determinant of <m>A</m> is defined by expansion along the first row:
        </p>
        <me>
          \det(A)
          =
          \sum_{j=1}^{n}
          a_{1j}\operatorname{cof}(A)_{1j}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <fact>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For an <m>n\times n</m> matrix, cofactor expansion along any row or any column gives the same determinant:
        </p>
        <me>
          \det(A)=\sum_{j=1}^{n} a_{ij}\operatorname{cof}(A)_{ij}
        </me>
        <p>
          for any fixed row <m>i</m>, and
        </p>
        <me>
          \det(A)=\sum_{i=1}^{n} a_{ij}\operatorname{cof}(A)_{ij}
        </me>
        <p>
          for any fixed column <m>j</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </fact>

    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the determinant of the matrix
          <me>
            A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 5 \amp 4 \amp 2 \amp 3\\ 1 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 5 \\ 3 \amp 4 \amp 3 \amp 2\end{bmatrix}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Expand along column <m>3</m>:
        </p>
        <me>
          \det(A)
          =
          3\operatorname{cof}(A)_{13}
          +
          2\operatorname{cof}(A)_{23}
          +
          4\operatorname{cof}(A)_{33}
          +
          3\operatorname{cof}(A)_{43}.
        </me>
        <p>
          The signs in column <m>3</m> are
        </p>
        <me>
          +,\ -,\ +,\ -.
        </me>
        <p>So</p>
        <md>
          <mrow>
            \det(A)
            \amp=
            3\det
            \begin{bmatrix}
            5\amp 4\amp 3\\
            1\amp 3\amp 5\\
            3\amp 4\amp 2
            \end{bmatrix}
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp\quad
            -
            2\det
            \begin{bmatrix}
            1\amp 2\amp 4\\
            1\amp 3\amp 5\\
            3\amp 4\amp 2
            \end{bmatrix}
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp\quad
            +
            4\det
            \begin{bmatrix}
            1\amp 2\amp 4\\
            5\amp 4\amp 3\\
            3\amp 4\amp 2
            \end{bmatrix}
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp\quad
            -
            3\det
            \begin{bmatrix}
            1\amp 2\amp 4\\
            5\amp 4\amp 3\\
            1\amp 3\amp 5
            \end{bmatrix}.
          </mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
          Using the <m>3\times 3</m> determinant method,
        </p>
        <me>
          \det
          \begin{bmatrix}
          5\amp 4\amp 3\\
          1\amp 3\amp 5\\
          3\amp 4\amp 2
          \end{bmatrix}
          =
          -33,
        </me>
        <me>
          \det
          \begin{bmatrix}
          1\amp 2\amp 4\\
          1\amp 3\amp 5\\
          3\amp 4\amp 2
          \end{bmatrix}
          =
          -8,
        </me>
        <me>
          \det
          \begin{bmatrix}
          1\amp 2\amp 4\\
          5\amp 4\amp 3\\
          3\amp 4\amp 2
          \end{bmatrix}
          =
          26,
        </me>
        <p>and</p>
        <me>
          \det
          \begin{bmatrix}
          1\amp 2\amp 4\\
          5\amp 4\amp 3\\
          1\amp 3\amp 5
          \end{bmatrix}
          =
          11.
        </me>
        <p>Therefore</p>
        <md>
          <mrow>
            \det(A)
            \amp=
            3(-33)-2(-8)+4(26)-3(11)
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp=
            -99+16+104-33
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp=
            -12.
          </mrow>
        </md>
      </solution>
    </activity>

    <activity xml:id="act-3-1-expansion-of-upper-triangular">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute <m>\det(A)</m>, where
          <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 4 \amp 2 \amp 3\\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 5 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -1\end{bmatrix}</me>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Expanding in cofactors along column <m>1</m> (because most of the entries of that column are zeros), we find
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \det(A) \amp = 3 \cdot \text{cof}(A)_{11} + 0 \cdot \text{cof}(A)_{21} + 0 \cdot \text{cof}(A)_{31} + 0 \cdot \text{cof}(A)_{41}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 3 (-1)^{1+1} \det \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp 5 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix} = 3 \det \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp 5 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}
            </mrow>.
          </md>
          Expanding along the first column again, we find that
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \det \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp 5 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix} \amp = 4 \det \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 5 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 4 ((2)(-1) - (5)(0)) = -8
            </mrow>
          </md>.
          So <m>\det(A) = (3)(-8) = -24 </m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>

    <p>
      Recall <xref ref="def-matrix-main-diagonal"/>.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-4-1-triangular-matrices">
      <title>Triangular and Diagonal Matrices</title>

      <statement>
        <p>
          An <m>n \times n</m> matrix <m>A = [ a_{ij} ]</m> is called <term>upper triangular</term> if <m>a_{ij} = 0</m> for <m>i > j</m>, and <term>lower triangular</term> if <m>a_{ij} = 0</m> for <m>i \lt j</m>. A matrix is <term>diagonal</term> if it is both upper triangular and lower triangular, i.e., if <m>a_{ij} = 0</m> for <m>i \neq j</m>. We denote the <m>n \times n</m> diagonal matrix with entries <m>\lambda_1,\dots, \lambda_n</m> on the diagonal by <m>\text{diag}(\lambda_1,\dots,\lambda_n)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>A = [a_{ij}]</m> is a upper or lower triangular matrix, then <m>\det(A) = a_{11} \cdots a_{nn}</m>. That is, the determinant of a triangular matrix is the product of entries in the <em>main diagonal</em>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          A generalization of the argument used to calculate <xref ref="act-3-1-expansion-of-upper-triangular" />, i.e., expanding the determinant in cofactors along the first column iteratively.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If a row or column of a matrix <m>A</m> consists entirely of zeros, then <m>\det(A) = 0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          A generalization of the argument used to calculate the determinant in <xref ref="task-3-1-0-column-example" />.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-3-1-swapping-rows-determinant">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If a matrix <m>B</m> is obtained from a matrix <m>A</m> by swapping two rows or two columns, then <m>\det(B) = - \det(A)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Check directly that <xref ref="thm-3-1-swapping-rows-determinant"/> is true when <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <m>2 \times 2</m> matrices.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          If
          <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}</me>
          and
          <me>B = \begin{bmatrix} c \amp d \\ a \amp b \end{bmatrix}</me>,
          then <m>\det(A) = ad - bc</m> and <m>\det(B) = cb - ad = - (ad - bc) = - \det(A)</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </activity>

    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If two rows (or columns) of <m>A</m> are equal to one another, then <m>\det(A) = 0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>B</m> be the matrix obtained by swapping the two identical rows / columns of <m>A</m>. Then <m>A = B</m>, and <xref ref="thm-3-1-swapping-rows-determinant"/> implies that <m>\det(A) = - \det(B) = - \det(A)</m>. Therefore <m>2 \det(A) = 0</m>, and thus that <m>\det(A) = 0</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>B</m> is obtained from <m>A</m> by multiplying each entry in a row or column of <m>A</m> by a quantity <m>k</m>, then <m>\det(B) = k \det(A)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose that <m>B</m> is obtained from <m>A</m> by multiplying each entry of row <m>i</m> by <m>k</m>. Consider a cofactor expansion along row <m>i</m> of <m>B</m>. Then
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \det(B) \amp = k a_{i1} \text{cof}(B)_{i1} + k a_{i2} \text{cof}(B)_{i2} + \cdots + k a_{in} \text{cof}(B)_{in}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = k [ a_{i1} \text{cof}(A)_{i1} + \cdots + a_{in} \text{cof}(A)_{in} ]
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = k \text{det}(A)
            </mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <fact>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>A</m> is a <m>n \times n</m> matrix, then <m>\det(kA) = k^n \det(A)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </fact>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-3-1-row-operation-determinant">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>B</m> is obtained by adding <m>k</m> times the <m>i</m>th row of <m>A</m> to the <m>j</m>th row, for <m>i \neq j</m>, which is a row operation which we denote by <m>R_j \rightarrow R_j + kR_i</m>, then <m>\det(B) = \det(A)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      We can check <xref ref="thm-3-1-row-operation-determinant"/> in the <m>2 \times 2</m> case. If
      <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}</me>
      and
      <me>B = \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c + ka \amp d + kb \end{bmatrix}</me>,
      then
      <me>\det(A) = ad - bc</me>
      and
      <md>
        <mrow>
          \det(B) \amp = a(d + kb) - b(c + ka)
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp= ad + kab - bc - kab
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp = ad - bc = \det(A)
        </mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>

    <theorem>
      <title>How row operations affect the determinant</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Here is a summary of how the elementary row operations, when applied to a matrix, affect the determinant:
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p><m>R_i \rightarrow k R_i</m> multiplies the determinant by <m>k</m>.</p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p><m>R_i \leftrightarrow R_j</m> multiplies the determinant by <m>-1</m>.</p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p><m>R_j \rightarrow R_j + kR_i</m> leaves the determinant unchanged.</p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose a matrix <m>B</m> is obtained from a matrix <m>A</m> by applying the following row operations:
          <ul>
            <li>
              <m>R_i \leftrightarrow R_j</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>R_4 \rightarrow 4R_4</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>R_3 \rightarrow R_3 + 3R_2</m>
            </li>
          </ul>
          If <m>\det(A) = 8</m>, what is the determinant of <m>B</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          <ul>
            <li><m>R_i \leftrightarrow R_j</m>  multiplies the determinant by <m>-1</m>.</li>
            <li><m>R_4 \rightarrow 4R_4</m> multiplies the determinant by <m>4</m>.</li>
            <li><m>R_3 \rightarrow R_3 + 3R_2</m> does not change the determinant.</li>
          </ul>
          Therefore <m>\det(B) = (-1)(4) \det(A) = -32</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>

    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute the determinant of the matrix
          <me>B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 3 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 15 \amp 12 \end{bmatrix}</me>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          We use the elementary row operations to make the matrix <m>B</m> triangular:

          <sbsgroup widths="30% 30%" margins="19% 19%" valign="middle">
            <sidebyside>
              <p>
                <me>R_2 \rightarrow R_2 + R_1</me>
              </p>

              <p>
                <me>
                  \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 5 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 15 \amp 12 \end{bmatrix}
                </me>
              </p>
            </sidebyside>

            <sidebyside>
              <p>
                <me>R_3 \rightarrow R_3 - 3 R_2</me>
              </p>

              <p>
                <me>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 5 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</me>
              </p>
            </sidebyside>
          </sbsgroup>

          None of the row operations we have performed change the determinant of the matrix, and the final matrix has determinant zero, so <m>\det(B) = 0</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>


  <theorem xml:id="thm-3-2-product-determinant">
  	<statement>
  		<p>
  			If <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <m>n \times n</m> matrices, then <m>\det(AB) = \det(A) \det(B)</m>.
  		</p>
  	</statement>
  </theorem>

  <activity>
  	<introduction>
  		<p>
  			Let
  			<me>A = \begin{bmatrix}3 \amp 1 \\ -2 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix} \quad B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix} \quad C = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</me>.
  		</p>
  	</introduction>

  	<task>
  		<statement>
  			<p>
				Compute the determinant of <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m>.
  			</p>
  		</statement>

  		<solution>
  			<p>
				We use the formula for <m>2 \times 2</m> matrices: First, that
				<me>
					\det(A) = (3)(7) - (1)(-2) = 23
				</me>,
				then that
				<me>
					\det(B) = (1)(4) - (2)(2) = 0
				</me>,
				and that
				<me>
					\det(C) = (1)(2) - (4)(0) = 2
				</me>.
  			</p>
  		</solution>
  	</task>

  	<task>
  		<statement>
  			<p>
				Compute the determinant of <m>AC</m> and <m>BC</m>.
  			</p>
  		</statement>

  		<solution>
  			<p>
				Using <xref ref="thm-3-2-product-determinant"/>, we calculate that
				<me>
				\det(AC) = \det(A) \det(C) = (23)(2) = 46
				</me>,
				and that
				<me>
					\det(BC) = \det(B) \det(C) = (0)(2) = 0
				</me>.
				Alternatively, we can calculate the products of the matrices, i.e., that
				<me>
					AC = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 14 \\ -2 \amp 6 \end{bmatrix}
				</me>
				and that
				<me>
					BC = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 8 \\ 2 \amp 16 \end{bmatrix}
				</me>,
				and calculate the determinants directly.
  			</p>
  		</solution>
  	</task>
  </activity>

  <theorem>
  	<statement>
  		<p>
  			If <m>A</m> is a <m>n \times n</m> matrix, then <m>A</m> is <em>nonsingular</em> if and only if <m>\det(A) \neq 0</m>. In this case <m>\det(A^{-1}) = 1 / \det(A)</m>.
  		</p>
  	</statement>

  	<proof>
  		<p>
        We prove only one direction of the theorem, that if <m>A</m> is nonsingular then <m>\det(A) \neq 0</m> and <m>\det(A^{-1}) = 1/\det(A)</m>. Suppose that <m>A</m> is non-singular. Then <m>A A^{-1} = I</m>. Taking determinants of both sides, and using that <m>I</m> is diagonal, so that <m>\det(I) = 1</m>, we see that
  		<me>1 = \det(I) = \det(A A^{-1}) = \det(A) \det(A^{-1})</me>.
  		Thus <m>\det(A) \neq 0</m> (since otherwise the right hand side of this equation would be zero), and rearranging gives <m>\det(A^{-1}) = 1/\det(A)</m>.
  	</p>
  	</proof>
  </theorem>

  <theorem>
  	<statement>
  		<p>
  			If <m>A</m> is a square matrix, then <m>\det(A) = \det(A^T)</m>.
  		</p>
  	</statement>
  </theorem>

  <definition xml:id="def-4-2-orthogonal">
    <title>Orthogonal Matrices</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A square matrix <m>A</m> is <term>orthogonal</term> if <m>A^T = A^{-1}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <activity>
  	<statement>
  		<p>
        If <m>A</m> is an orthogonal matrix, what are the possible values of <m>\det(A)</m>?
  		</p>
  	</statement>

  	<solution>
  		<p>
  			If <m>A</m> is orthogonal, then applying the determinant to both sides of the equation <m>I = AA^T</m> gives
  			<me>1 = \det(I) = \det(AA^T) = \det(A) \det(A^T) = \det(A)^2</me>.
  			Taking square roots gives that <m>\det(A) = \pm 1</m>.
  		</p>
  	</solution>
  </activity>

</subsection>
